name: 3-fluoro-4-methoxybenzenesulfonamide
Reason: 3-fluoro-4-methoxybenzenesulfonamide has a melting point that we will compare to benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5°C (according to the CRC Handbook of Chemistry and Physics, 49th Edition, 1968-1969). The basic unit for our comparison is benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5°C. The fluorine atom introduces a significant increase in melting point due to strong electronegativity, which leads to stronger intermolecular dipole-dipole interactions. The methoxy group also contributes to the melting point due to increased molecular weight and size. The sulfonamide group can also participate in hydrogen bonding, which may lower the melting point. The net effect is a complex interplay of structural and functional group effects.
